  "text": "Nature Video 08 May 2025 DNA sequencing of a family from children to great-grandparents reveals more mutations than previously seen. By Shamini Bundell Dan Fox You have full access to this article via your institution. Human de novo mutation rates from a four-generation pedigree reference The DNA of each child that is born contains entirely new mutations, not found in either of their parents. To find out how much that DNA changes, and how fast the human genome mutates, researchers compared the genomes from four generations of a single family. They found mutation hotspots in our chromosomes and discovered more and bigger changes than we previously knew about. doi: https://doi.org/10.1038/d41586-025-01473-6 Related Articles Watch: G﻿aps in our genes are more important than we thought ‘Like a moth to a flame’ - This strange insect behaviour is finally explained The Physics of Fish Hearing Inside the ant lab: Mutants and social genes Bumblebees show uniquely human behaviour Fossilised glider takes the origin of mammals back to the Triassic Jungle Genetics Subjects Latest on:",
